It wasn't &quot;some sort of incentive to pay full retail price&quot; but, rather,
an incentive for people to head for the (non-returnable) direct-market
stores in the early 1980s that led to the industry providing books to
that nascent direct market three full weeks earlier than they released
them to other channels (newsstands, bookstores).

Remember the old MARVEL AGE and DIRECT CURRENTS new-release lists that
had two dates for each book? One that was a &quot;Shipping Date&quot; that
correlated within a couple of days to when you could go to a specialty
shop for your books, followed by an &quot;Available Date&quot; about three weeks
later that correlated to when you could go into 7-11 or WaldenBooks and
get the version with the UPC on the cover?

Presumably, sub copies were mailed at bulk library rate (aka &quot;bound
printed matter&quot;) around the shipping date, but given their low-priority
status with the USPS, it might take three weeks for sub copies to
actually reach subscribers.

(And they =looked= like they'd been in the hands of the Postal Service
that long when they finally did show up. I remember copies of Simonson's
THOR arriving looking as if they'd been used to line the cages of Michael
Vick's kennels...)

